Now, instead of using prcomp we will do the analysis ourselves using the eigen command.

  • Start by computing the sample mean and sample variance of the dataset (use \(n-1\) as the denominator when you compute the sample variance to get the same answer as provided by prcomp).
Solution 
xbar = colMeans(X)
cov(X)
             Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
Sepal.Length    0.6856935  -0.0424340    1.2743154   0.5162707

Petal.Length    1.2743154  -0.3296564    3.1162779   1.2956094
Petal.Width     0.5162707  -0.1216394    1.2956094   0.5810063
Xcent = sweep(X,2,xbar) # HX
S = t(Xcent)%*%Xcent/149 # should agree with cov(X)
  • Now compute the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the covariance matrix using eigen. Check that these agree with those computed by prcomp (noting that prcomp returns the standard deviation which is the square root of the eigenvalues).

What has gone wrong - why don’t they agree? Two things have happened. Firstly there are small numerical errors that occur due to rounding errors. The second is that the eigenvectors are only determined upto multiplication by \(\pm 1\). If we divide them, we can see they are essentially the same:

X.pca$rotation/S.eig$vectors 
             PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4
Sepal.Length   1  -1  -1   1
Sepal.Width    1  -1  -1   1
Petal.Length   1  -1  -1   1
Petal.Width    1  -1  -1   1

We can also check that the standard deviations agree with the eigenvalues.

X.pca$sdev^2
[1] 4.22824171 0.24267075 0.07820950 0.02383509
S.eig$values
[1] 4.22824171 0.24267075 0.07820950 0.02383509
X.pca$sdev^2- S.eig$values
[1]  3.552714e-15  3.330669e-16  8.326673e-17 -1.491862e-16
  • Now compute the principal component scores by multiplying \(\mathbf X\) by the matrix of eigenvectors \(\mathbf V\). Check your answer agrees with the scores provided by prcomp.
Solution 
scores = Xcent%*%S.eig$vectors 
## note must use Xcent!

head(X.pca$x/ scores)

[4,]   1  -1  -1   1
[5,]   1  -1  -1   1
[6,]   1  -1  -1   1

So the scores (transformed variables) agree.

Now we will do the same thing again, but using the svd command.

  • Compute the column centred data matrix \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\).
Solution 
Xtilde = Xcent/sqrt(149)
  • Compute the SVD of \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\) and \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\). How are the two sets of singular values related, and how do they relate to the eigenvalues computed previously. Are the singular vectors of \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n-1}}\mathbf H\mathbf X\) and \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\) the same?
Solution

Iif we scale \(X\), then the singular values are scaled by the same amount.

  • Compute the SVD scores by doing both \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\mathbf V\) and \(\mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\), where \[\mathbf H\mathbf X= \mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\mathbf V^\top\] is the SVD of \(\mathbf H\mathbf X\).

Q2

In this question we will look at the crabs data from the MASS R package. We will focus on the 5 continuous variables, all measured in mm:

  • FL = frontal lobe size
  • RW = rear width
  • CL = carapace length
  • CW = carapace width
  • BD = body depth.
library(MASS)
?crabs # look at the help page.
X = crabs[,4:8]
  • Carry out PCA on the data in \(X\) using the covariance matrix, including obtaining a scree plot and plotting the PC scores.
Solution 
crabs.pca <- prcomp(X) # do PCA
plot(crabs.pca) # scree plot

plot(crabs.pca$x[,1], crabs.pca$x[,2]) # PC2 vs PC1.

By adding colour we can see some patterns. The easiest way is to install the ggfortify package.

library(ggfortify)
autoplot(crabs.pca, data = crabs, colour='sp', scale=FALSE)

This has coloured the points by species. We can see there is clearly a difference between blue and orange crabs (confusingly coloured opposite to their name here).

If we colour by species and change the shape according to sex, we can see distinct clusters.

autoplot(crabs.pca, data = crabs, colour='sp', scale=FALSE, shape='sex')

  • Do you have any suggestions for an interpretation for the first two principal components?
Solution

The first PC appears to be a measure of size, primarily carapace size:

crabs.pca$rotation[,1]
       FL        RW        CL        CW        BD 
0.2889810 0.1972824 0.5993986 0.6616550 0.2837317

The second PC measures FL and RW vs carapace size.

crabs.pca$rotation[,2]
        FL         RW         CL         CW         BD 
 0.3232500  0.8647159 -0.1982263 -0.2879790  0.1598447

There is a clear sex dependence here; female crabs have higher positive PC2 score (corresponding to big FL, RW, BD, and smaller Carapace).

autoplot(crabs.pca, data = crabs, colour='sex')

  • Do you think an analysis based on the sample covariance matrix \({\bf S}\) or the correlation matrix \({\bf R}\) is preferable with this dataset?
Solution

This doesn’t make a big difference but does alter the interpretations a little.

crabs.pca2 <- prcomp(X, scale=TRUE) # Use the correlation matrix.
plot(crabs.pca2)

autoplot(crabs.pca2, data = crabs, colour='sex')

# not a big change

PC1 is still a measure of size, but now evenly weights across all attributes. PC2 is changed from the unscaled PCA, and it now measures the difference in RW to the other attributes.

crabs.pca2$rotation[,1]
       FL        RW        CL        CW        BD 
0.4520437 0.4280774 0.4531910 0.4511127 0.4511336 
crabs.pca2$rotation[,2]
        FL         RW         CL         CW         BD 
 0.1375813 -0.8981307  0.2682381  0.1805959  0.2643219

Another way to interpret the PCs is to look at circle plots

library(factoextra) # you will need to install this first time you use it.
fviz(crabs.pca2, element='var')

This gives the correlation between the first two transformed variables and the original variables.

cor(cbind(crabs.pca2$x[,1:2], X))[3:7,1:2]
         PC1         PC2
FL 0.9892256  0.05358348
RW 0.9367791 -0.34979304
CL 0.9917363  0.10447013
CW 0.9871883  0.07033629
BD 0.9872340  0.10294487

Why is it plotted on a circle? It is possible to show that \[\sum_{j=1}^p {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(y_j, x_i)^2 = 1\] where \(x_i\) are the original variables, and \(y_j\) the transformed variables.

Thus for any of the original variables \(x_i\) we have that \[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(y_1, x_i)^2+{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(y_2, x_i)^2 \leq 1\] i.e., they lie within a circle.

We can do similar plots for the unscaled version of PCA. But now we’re plotting variances and so these points do not lie in a cirle.

fviz(crabs.pca, element='var')

So we can see again that in the unscaled case, PC1 is a measure of overall size, but particularly CL and CW. PC2 is RW, FL, BD versus CL and CW.

Orthogonal rotations:

If we multiply the data by an orthogonal matrix the scores and eigenvalues remain the same but the loadings/eigenvectors change.

U <- randortho(5)
X4 = as.matrix(X)%*% U

Q3

Download the final Premier League table for the 2022-23 season from https://www.rotowire.com/soccer/league-table.php?season=2022. There is a button to download the csv (comma separated variable) file in the bottom right hand corner. Note that you may need to manually delete the first row of the csv file before doing this. (I haven’t given you the command here, as learning how to do this yourself is important).

Repeat the analysis done in the notes.

Solution 
library(dplyr)
prem22 <- read.csv('~/Documents/Teaching/MATH3030_4068/ComputerTaskSolutions/prem202223.csv') 
# the data can be downloaded from https://www.rotowire.com/soccer/league-table.php
table <- prem22 %>% dplyr::select(Team, W, D, L, G, GA, GD) 
knitr::kable(head(table,10), booktabs = TRUE, escape=FALSE)
Team W D L G GA GD
Manchester City 28 5 5 94 33 61

rownames(tmp)=table$Team

prem.pca = prcomp(tmp, retx=TRUE, scale=TRUE)
prem.pca$rotation[,1]
          W           D           L           G          GA          GD 
-0.45998030  0.05857796  0.45679455 -0.43021007  0.41006143 -0.47232871 
fviz(prem.pca, element='var')

autoplot(prem.pca, data = table,  label = TRUE,  label.size = 3, shape=FALSE)

PC1 is remarkably similar to the 2019-20 season. It contrasts goals against and losses vs goals for and wins (ie it measures if the team did well or not). PC2 is mainly measures the number of draws a team had. So Newcastle had lots of draws, and thus had a very small PC2 score. Manchester city won the legue so have the smallest PC1 score. Southampton finished bottom and have the largest PC1 score.
